result.execSummary:
The defendant Joshua M. Anderson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Burglary-Building or Dwelling [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(a).
  • Possession of Burglarious Tools [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.12.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Joshua M. Anderson in court, in custody & via-video from Oshkosh Correctional Facility.  Ralph Malcom Uttke appeared for the State of Wisconsin.   Court calls  @ 9:01 am. J.A. duly sworn on oath, testifies. Def. heard on $100 bill, Samsung Tablet, 30-$5 bills, 118-$1.00, Samsung 3 cell phone, State will not object to cell phone & tablet.  Shoes, sweatshirt, jean, &  brewer shirt, State does not object. State questions def. on money. off the record @ 9:12 am. Back on the record @ 9:13 am. The only thing in dispute is the currency.  Def. makes argument. Deputy is present in courtroom. Def. has not witness. off the record @ 9:17 a.m. back on the record @ 9:21 am.  Eric Chernetski, Deputy for Langlade County Sheriff Dept., duly sworn on oath, testifies. State has no more.  Def. gives argument.  State gives argument. Def. responds. Parties have reached a stipulation to return #40, #58, & #62, #63, #64 & brewer shirt unnumber. Court finds State has no evidence, & will return money to def, but will stay order for 10 days if State comes with evidence on ownership of money than Court will hear otherwise money will be returned.  State questions Court ruling.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Joshua M. Anderson in court with attorney Zachary Glascock.  Defendant Joshua M. Anderson in custody.  Ralph Malcom Uttke appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  10:30 a.m./On plea to both counts, joint recommendation:  Ct. 1/5 years prison, 2 years confinement, 3 years extended supervision, credit 99 days, concurrent with present prison sentence.  Extended supervision conditions:  restitution $1,023.00 joint & several, costs, counselling, eligible for both programs.  Ct. 2 - sentence withheld, 3 years probation concurrent with Ct. 1 with conditions:  costs, counselling.  Compliance with victim rights law.  Def. given right to preliminary hearing.  Waiver of preliminary hearing filed with the Court.  Def. waives preliminary hearing.  Information filed.  Def. has copy and waives reading.  Plea questionnaire and waiver of rights form filed with Court.  Ct. 1 - burglary - no contest plea.  Ct. 2 - Poss. Burglarious Tools - no contest plea.  Court reviews Def.'s constitutional rights.  Def. understands waiving JT.  Court reviews elements with Def.  Def. understands penalties.  Def. advised of voting and firearm rights.  Def. advised of possible deportation if not US citizen.  Court finds Def. has freely and voluntarily entered pleas.  Parties stipulate factual basis.  Court finds factual basis and accepts pleas and finds Def. guilty of both counts.  State makes sentencing argument.  Def.'s Atty. makes sentencing argument.  Discussion about Def.'s past criminal record.  Def. makes statement to Court.  Court orders on Ct. 1 - 5 years prison, 2 years initial confinement, 3 years extended supervision with conditions:  costs, restitution $1,023.00 joint and several.  Credit 99 days.  Ct. 1 concurrent with 0utagamie cases 07-CF-587, 08-CF-23.  DNA sample and surcharge.  Def. has right to petition for expunction of DNA sample if eligible.  Ct. 2 - sentence withheld, 3 years probation concurrent with Ct. 1 with conditions:  costs, DNA surcharge.   Def. is eligible for Challenge Incarceration and Substance Abuse Programs.  Def. is advised of firearm and voting rights.    If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered, without further order of the court, against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.  Def. advised of postconviction rights.  Both counts are party to.  Counselling on both counts as recommended by agent.
